01:09:43,259 --> 01:09:48,620
And I guess there could be some type of breaksmanship where the municipal government then decided to appropriate more.

679
01:09:48,660 --> 01:10:01,363
But just frankly, the way the municipal governments operate and the timing that's involved here in terms of the start of the fiscal year, that wouldn't be a strategically prudent route to take, which is why committees typically don't take that route.

680
01:10:03,018 --> 01:10:16,507
So again, that's a, I think trying to articulate that and sharing that type of doomsday scenario, I'm not sure I would say that it would help inform the community.

681
01:10:16,607 --> 01:10:28,815
I think in large part, it would be articulating an option, creating the perception that it's a viable one when in fact it's really not a viable option and one that,

682
01:10:30,906 --> 01:10:37,268
I just, I'm hesitant to incorporate more information into this type of presentation that I think is just going to confuse people.

683
01:10:41,029 --> 01:10:46,650
But the committee is certainly, I'm not trying to substitute my judgment for the committee.

684
01:10:47,150 --> 01:10:58,213
The committee would like to articulate the step-by-step what would happen if the committee voted to not allow the administration to spend the money that was appropriated.

685
01:10:59,732 --> 01:11:00,653
certainly entitled to do that.

686
01:11:01,233 --> 01:11:13,123
I think my recommendation at the time would be to adopt the budget that was appropriated and continue to advocate for a supplemental appropriation to help bridge whatever gaps the committee recognized.

687
01:11:13,243 --> 01:11:19,548
I think that would be a significantly more prudent strategy than shutting the school department down on July 1st.

688
01:11:25,993 --> 01:11:26,613
Member Rousseau.

689
01:11:28,575 --> 01:11:28,915
Thank you.

690
01:11:29,977 --> 01:11:31,958
I'm feeling a bit of deja vu here.

691
01:11:35,100 --> 01:11:45,025
I've literally watched videos in this last year of communities that have school committees that send budgets up far greater than their municipal appropriation and the world doesn't come to an end.

692
01:11:46,085 --> 01:11:51,528
Can you explain to me why that isn't actually an option for us?

693
01:11:52,208 --> 01:11:57,691
I think it's a very reasonable option with regard to your vote to make that request.

694
01:11:58,589 --> 01:12:07,876
I'm talking about the scenario in which the budget has passed through the municipal government and where we get to the point at which the new fiscal year is going to start.

695
01:12:08,456 --> 01:12:28,310
And what I'm saying is rather than refusing to adopt that budget and therefore freezing the administration's ability to expend any of the resources that have been appropriated, I think it would be a more prudent strategy to adopt that budget and then continue to advocate and lobby the branch of the municipal government that does have spending authority to supplement that budget.

696
01:12:29,748 --> 01:12:30,829
I'm sorry, I wasn't clear.

697
01:12:31,629 --> 01:12:40,474
So if the mayor through her office gives you a number, the school committee's authority around the budget is to vote yes or no on that number.

698
01:12:41,015 --> 01:12:44,937
That is our entire, we have all these meetings, we have all this process.

699
01:12:45,397 --> 01:12:48,559
At the end of the day, we're voting yes or no on the number that the mayor gave us.

700
01:12:49,040 --> 01:12:51,821
And that is the entirety of what we do.

701
01:12:52,682 --> 01:12:58,085
I'm saying in other communities, we develop a budget based on the school committee's priorities and obviously,

702
01:12:58,672 --> 01:13:03,373
with the administration and we send up an $85 million budget.

703
01:13:03,913 --> 01:13:11,155
And the mayor says in her budget, it's 65 million and sends it to the city council and they approve it for $65 million.

704
01:13:11,375 --> 01:13:19,777
And we can go to sleep with a good conscience because we talk about priorities, getting to the priorities that have been on our lists.

705
01:13:20,157 --> 01:13:23,698
We talk about that like it's like new uniforms for the band.

706
01:13:23,818 --> 01:13:24,658
No, we're talking about,

707
01:13:25,606 --> 01:13:33,387
reading services for kids in high school that are not on IEPs that can't read well enough to get through life.

708
01:13:34,248 --> 01:13:40,969
We have zero reading service providers for kids that are not on IEPs that do not read properly, sufficiently.

709
01:13:41,809 --> 01:13:43,609
That's not a priority.

710
01:13:43,709 --> 01:13:46,810
Those are kids for going out into the world without basic skills.

711
01:13:47,390 --> 01:13:50,691
And, you know, I mean, there's the middle school sex ed that we don't have.

712
01:13:51,251 --> 01:13:53,271
We don't have any physical ed

713
01:13:53,738 --> 01:13:56,219
We don't have an adaptive physical ed person.

714
01:13:58,180 --> 01:14:04,042
We keep talking about priorities, like we're talking about whether to get a new car this year or wait a year, like it's our personal budget.

715
01:14:05,483 --> 01:14:11,445
There are actual children on the other end who are going off out of our schools, not prepared to survive.

716
01:14:12,645 --> 01:14:22,029
And so I would be able to go to bed if we sent an $85 million budget up, just picking a number randomly, that reflected what we said we needed.

717
01:14:24,015 --> 01:14:32,900
And then it's on the mayor and then it's on the city council and it's on the taxpayers who will then not be able to deny that this is what we need.

718
01:14:33,180 --> 01:14:38,463
But every year we send up a budget that is the exact to the nickel number we're given from the city hall.

719
01:14:39,103 --> 01:14:40,524
And it doesn't matter what we need.

720
01:14:41,024 --> 01:14:41,804
It doesn't matter.

721
01:14:41,905 --> 01:14:42,685
And that's true.

722
01:14:43,906 --> 01:14:52,050
So I just, you know, this notion that we are in a, we're in a machine and we have no other options is just not true.

723
01:14:52,405 --> 01:14:54,045
and other communities have figured it out.

724
01:14:54,586 --> 01:14:59,787
They send a budget up that is ethical and reflects the needs of the kids.

725
01:15:01,447 --> 01:15:04,488
And if the community isn't willing to pay for it, then it's on the community.

726
01:15:04,788 --> 01:15:07,009
But if we won't send that budget up, it's on us.

727
01:15:07,209 --> 01:15:09,469
It's not on the community, it's on us.

728
01:15:11,650 --> 01:15:14,470
I'm just tired of this talk about priorities.

729
01:15:14,510 --> 01:15:18,972
It's like whether or not to paint your house this year or next, or this year or not.

730
01:15:20,988 --> 01:15:22,688
Mayor, if I could just respond briefly.

731
01:15:23,109 --> 01:15:28,210
I just want to be clear in this presentation, we've used the word necessity, not priority.

732
01:15:28,970 --> 01:15:36,052
So I think that I understand what you're saying that I would say I would rather use the term strategic priority than wishlist.

733
01:15:36,132 --> 01:15:44,634
And that is something that we've talked to within our internal budget meetings, we've made that expectation clear, because I think a wishlist, frankly, doesn't sound credible.

734
01:15:44,734 --> 01:15:50,575
And I think that you're not in a position to be able to advocate on behalf of the school department, if we are

735
01:15:51,088 --> 01:15:55,050
asking everyone who works for us to say, just tell us what you dream about at night.

736
01:15:55,090 --> 01:15:57,931
I don't think that helps the cause in any way.

737
01:15:58,391 --> 01:16:10,256
But I hope, Mr. Rousseau, you're not taking this presentation to suggest that we as an administration believe you don't have any options.

738
01:16:10,556 --> 01:16:20,400
The presentation tonight says there's a range from 3.4 to 5.8 that we can make very good, very prudent, very student-centered,

739
01:16:21,252 --> 01:16:21,972
investments in.

740
01:16:22,592 --> 01:16:34,256
Now, as you hear from department heads over the course of the next several weeks, you may well say 5.8 seems, you know, important, but we really think it's 6.3.

741
01:16:35,116 --> 01:16:40,758
I can't, frankly, I don't know why you wouldn't make that request if that's what you think is necessary.

742
01:16:41,058 --> 01:16:47,259
Because to your point, the sky is not going to fall in if the committee says, look, we've summed all this up.

743
01:16:47,660 --> 01:16:48,900
We think the vote should be at 6.3.

744
01:16:49,882 --> 01:16:53,983
should be 6.3 is ultimately it is the school committee's request to make.

745
01:16:54,103 --> 01:16:55,863
You should make it as you see fit.

746
01:16:56,524 --> 01:17:08,486
I would say I have a responsibility to tell you that if we get much further past the range that we're talking about here, again, there's a lot of planning that would have to go in.

747
01:17:08,686 --> 01:17:17,488
And so I would be mindful of that for purposes of making sure that we as an organization have the credibility to advocate on behalf of students.

748
01:17:17,528 --> 01:17:19,629
I think that that's sort of how this

749
01:17:20,243 --> 01:17:25,525
works when you have multi levers of government involved in the development of a budget.

750
01:17:25,625 --> 01:17:28,786
But I think by all means, you can make that request.

751
01:17:28,826 --> 01:17:30,847
I don't know why you wouldn't.

752
01:17:32,568 --> 01:17:37,870
Understand that we're going to be able to operate if we end up with less than that.

753
01:17:38,190 --> 01:17:48,154
And what we as an administration can't do is, and I don't think anyone is asking us to do to be clear, but we can't say, we can't light our hair on fire if

754
01:17:48,688 --> 01:17:57,352
you know, if the request comes in below $6 million because we are going to be able to operate, we're going to be able to do right by students.

755
01:17:57,952 --> 01:18:01,733
If we get lower than that low end of the number, no, I don't think we can.

756
01:18:01,753 --> 01:18:17,640
I have a responsibility to tell you from based on what I've seen so far, including a lot of these fixes that we're making and trying to be more transparent and be more honest and taking into account that those uncertainties, if we land at a number that is our current budget, less, you know, with less than a,

757
01:18:18,266 --> 01:18:19,647
a $3.4 million increase.

758
01:18:19,787 --> 01:18:21,827
At this time, I would not be comfortable with that.

759
01:18:22,228 --> 01:18:26,850
We would have to make a series of decisions that I don't think would be in the best interest of students.

760
01:18:27,250 --> 01:18:34,413
But I also would say, I don't think there's a magic number that somehow if we cross that threshold, all of a sudden, we're going to do right by every single kid.

761
01:18:34,653 --> 01:18:35,733
I don't think that number exists.

762
01:18:35,873 --> 01:18:38,034
I think right now, it's a range.

763
01:18:38,214 --> 01:18:40,335
I think there are a lot of variables that we have to take into account.

764
01:18:40,735 --> 01:18:42,296
I think there are questions that we have to answer.

765
01:18:44,277 --> 01:18:47,698
But I don't think, I just want to be clear that

766
01:18:48,156 --> 01:18:50,817
There's two stages of this process.

767
01:18:51,398 --> 01:19:07,746
You can make whatever request you think is appropriate, but I, it is hard to imagine a scenario on June 30th where not adopting the budget that's been appropriated is the best course of action.

768
01:19:07,946 --> 01:19:08,746
That was my only point.

769
01:19:09,287 --> 01:19:14,269
But prior to that, I think you should make whatever request you think is in the interest of the district.

770
01:19:16,287 --> 01:19:16,787
Thank you, Mayor.

771
01:19:16,827 --> 01:19:18,288
Mayor, may I just have a quick follow-up?

772
01:19:19,189 --> 01:19:19,769
Member Rousseau.

773
01:19:21,010 --> 01:19:21,270
Thank you.

774
01:19:21,330 --> 01:19:25,933
Can we get an attorney who can answer the questions about this onto a meeting?

775
01:19:26,693 --> 01:19:36,799
Because I was under the impression from our last round was that if we had voted the budget down and the city appropriated the funds anyways, our voting it down would have no impact at all on people getting paid.

776
01:19:37,299 --> 01:19:43,023
So, you know, the notion that we shut the building down on July 1st and you all just go home

